h-Paper12-Q10","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":10,"marks":2,"topics":["Mensuration"],"s":"5.2","d":1,"cat":"mensuration","topic":"Area and perimeter","qtype":"area and perimeter","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/25 Q10","year":2025,"session":"March","tex":"A shape is drawn on a 1\\,cm$^2$ grid.\n\n(a) Find the area of the shape.\n\n(b) On the grid, shade 50\\% of the shape.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2025March-Paper12-Q11","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":11,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/25 Q11","year":2025,"session":"March","tex":"\\fbox{\\(19.5 \\times 20.4 = 397.8\\)}\nWork out.\n\n(a) $1.95 \\times 2.04$\n\n(b) $3978\\div 204$","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025March-Paper12-Q12","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":12,"marks":4,"topics":["Mensuration"],"s":"5.4","d":1,"cat":"mensuration","topic":"Surface area and volume","qtype":"surface area and volume","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/25 Q12","year":2025,"session":"March","tex":"%(a)\n\nKat has a method for finding the difference between two square numbers, \\(a^2 - b^2\\). \\\\\nHer method is\n\n(the sum of \\(a\\) and \\(b\\)) \\(\\times\\) (the difference between \\(a\\) and \\(b\\)).\n  She shows her method for \\(17^2 - 13^2\\).\n\n\\fbox{\n  \\begin{minipage}{0.32\\textwidth}\n   \\begin{align*}\n    &17^2 - 13^2 \\\\\n    &= (17 + 13) \\times (17 - 13) \\\\\n    &= 30 \\times 4 \\\\\n    &= 120\\\\\n   \\end{align*}\n  \\end{minipage}\n }\n\\medskip\n\n  Work out \\(29^2 - 21^2\\) using Kat's method.\\\\[3cm]\n\n(b)\n\nIn this part, all lengths are in centimetres.\n\nThe diagram shows a prism.\n\nWork out the volume of the prism.","parts":[],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025March-Paper12-Q13","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":13,"marks":1,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/25 Q13","year":2025,"session":"March","tex":"Convert $8$ litres into cm$^3$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025March-Paper12-Q14","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":14,"marks":7,"topics":["Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"4.6","d":1,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Angles","qtype":"angle calculations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/25 Q14","year":2025,"session":"March","tex":"The diagram shows a triangular prism.\n\n$ABC$ is an isosceles triangle with $AC = BC$.\n\nThe perpendicular height of triangle $ABC$ is 4\\,cm.\n\n$AB = 6$\\,cm and $BD = 6$\\,cm.\n\n(a) Complete this statement.\n\nThe prism has  faces and  edges.\n\n(b) Show that the length of $BC$ is 5\\,cm.\n\n\\newpage\n\n(c) Complete the net of the prism on the 1\\,cm$^2$ grid.\n\nThe base has been drawn for you.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":2},{"label":"(c)","marks":3}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"analyse","cmd":"show"},{"id":"0580-2025March-Paper12-Q15","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":15,"marks":5,"topics":["Geometry"],"s":"4.6","d":1,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Angles","qtype":"angle calculations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/25 Q15","year":2025,"session":"March","tex":"The diagram shows a triangle $BCD$ and a straight line $ABC$.\n\n$DB = DC = BC$.\n\n(a) Write down the mathematical name for triangle $BCD$.\n\n(b) Work out the value of $y$.\n\nGive two geometrical reasons for your answer.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":4}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025March-Paper12-Q16","paper":"2025March-Paper12","qnum":16,"marks":2,"topics":["Statistics"],"s":"9.5","d":1,"cat":"statistics","topic":"Scatter diagrams and correlation","qtype":"scatter diagrams","